definition.value: A baryon which contain one or more strange quarks. Hyperons are short-lived and heavier than nucleons.
A first-generation quark with a charge of +2/3. The up and down quarks are the fundamental constituents of the nucleons.
A first-generation quark with a charge of -1/3. The up and down quarks are the fundamental constituents of the nucleons.
A second-generation quark with a charge of -1/3 and a strangeness of -1.
A second-generation quark with a charge of +2/3.
The monohydrochloride salt of chloroprocaine. Used as a local anaesthetic, particularly for oral surgery, it has the advantage over lidocaine of constricting blood vessels, so reducing bleeding.
A third-generation quark with a charge of -1/3.
A third-generation quark with a charge of +2/3.
The cis-isomer of dipyrrin.
The trans-isomer of dipyrrin.

An aminoquinoline that is quinoline which is substituted at position 4 by a [5-(diethylamino)pentan-2-yl]amino group at at position 7 by chlorine. It is used for the treatment of malaria, hepatic amoebiasis, lupus erythematosus, light-sensitive skin eruptions, and rheumatoid arthritis.
An organochlorine compound comprising acetic acid carrying two chloro substituents at the 2-position. It occurs in nature in seaweed, Asparagopsis taxiformis.
A compound derived from an alkene by replacing a hydrogen atom with a chlorine atom.

A dinitrile that is benzene-1,3-dicarbonitrile substituted by four chloro groups. A non-systemic fungicide first introduced in the 1960s, it is used to control a range of diseases in a wide variety of crops.
A saturated organic heteromonocyclic parent that is an analogue of morpholine where the oxygen atom is replaced by sulfur.

4H-1,2,4-benzothiadiazine 1,1-dioxide in which the hydrogen at position is substituted by chlorine and that at position 7 is substituted by a sulfonamide group. A diuretic, it is used for treatment of oedema and hypertension.
An unsaturated monocyclic hydrocarbon having two endocyclic double bonds.
An unsaturated monocyclic hydrocarbon having three endocyclic double bonds.
A monocyclic hydrocarbon having any number of double bonds.
A cycloalkene that is cylohexane with a single double bond.
An alpha-amino acid that is caproic acid substituted by an amino group at position 2.
